|-
! colspan="5"| Thresholds per award
|-
! colspan="5"| "—" denotes that an award is not given by the certifying body.
|}

note|Digital albums| I Australian, Belgian, Danish, Finnish, German, Hungarian, Mexican, Norwegian, Polish, Spanish, Swedish, British and American figures can include digital album sales.<br />
note|Middle East| II GCC sales refer to sales in Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and UAE.<ref>cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/SALES_AWARD_APPLICATION_FORM-MIDDLE_EAST.pdf|format=PDF|title=IFPI Middle East Award application form</ref><br />
note|German albums| III For German sales, the thresholds in the table are for albums released from January 1, 2003. For albums released until September 24, 1999 the thresholds are 250,000 for Gold and 500,000 for Platinum. For albums released between September 25, 1999 and December 31, 2002 the thresholds are 150,000 for Gold and 300,000 for Platinum. Also, for Jazz albums, the thresholds are 10,000 for Gold and 20,000 for Platinum. Diamond-award is applicable to titles released on/after January 1, 2013.<ref name="BVMI" /> <br />
note|Hungarian albums| IV Hungarian sales figures provided refer to "Pop" albums. A separate scale is used for jazz, spoken word, classical, and world music albums: sales exceeding 1,500 and 3,000 for Gold and Platinum awards respectively.<br /> 
note|India| V Indian figures provided refer to "Hindi Films" and "International" scales. However, there are six separate release scales in all. Each scale is provided here with Gold and Platinum sales thresholds in parentheses: "Hindi Films" (100,000; 200,000); "Regional Films" (50,000; 100,000); "Regional Basic" (25,000, 50,000); "National Basic" (50,000; 100,000); "Classical/Non-Classical" (15,000; 30,000); and "International" (4,000; 6,000). In addition, there is a time limit for an album in one of the categories to reach gold and platinum, which is in one calendar year (for example: albums released on July 1, 2006, has only until June 30, 2007 for a Gold or Platinum award).<br />
note|Malaysian albums| VI Malaysian sales figures provided refer to albums released after 1 July 2009. For albums released before 1 July 2009, sales exceeding 10,000 and 20,000 for Gold and Platinum awards, respectively. Physical albums only; when combined with digital sales, thresholds are 15,000 for Gold and 30,000 for Platinum, whereby the digital sales are counted as 1/10 actual digital sales (10 downloads = 1 unit).<br />
note|Mexico| VII Mexican sales figures provided refer to physical album sales. A separate scale is used for digital album sales via digital download: sales exceeding 5,000 and 10,000 for Gold and Platinum awards respectively. Thresholds for productions before 1&nbsp;July 2009 differ: 40,000; 80,000; and 400,000 for Gold, Platinum, and Diamond, respectively (see AMPROFON for full details). Note that Mexico awards incremental Gold certifications even after Platinum has been achieved, so that an album may hold, for example, 2×Platinum+Gold certification.<br />
note|Netherlands| VIII Dutch sales figures provided refer to "Popular" albums. A separate scale is used for jazz, classical, and world music albums: sales exceeding 10,000 and 20,000 for Gold and Platinum awards respectively.<br />
note|Polish albums| IX Polish sales figures provided refer to "Pop" albums. Separate scales are used for jazz/classical albums, and soundtracks. Each scale is provided here with Gold, Platinum, and Diamond sales thresholds in parentheses: "Jazz/Classical" (5,000; 10,000; 50,000); and "Soundtracks" (10,000; 20,000; 100,000).<br />
note|Sweden| X Swedish sales figures provided refer to "Pop" albums. A separate scale is used for children, jazz, classical, and folk music albums: sales exceeding 10,000 and 20,000 for Gold and Platinum awards respectively.<br />
note|South Africa| XI South African sales figures provided refer to albums released after 1 December 2015. For albums released before 1 December 2015 but after 1 August 2006, a Gold award is given for sales exceeding 20,000 and a Platinum award for sales exceeding 40,000. For albums released before 1 August 2006, a Gold award is given for sales exceeding 25,000, a Platinum award for sales exceeding 50,000.<ref>cite web|url=http://www.risa.org.za/gold-platinum/certification-levels/ |title=RiSA Certification Levels |publisher=RiSA |accessdate=2018-04-01 </ref><br />
note|United Kingdom| XII United Kingdom thresholds were established in 1979 for albums above a minimum tooltip|RRP|Recommended Retail Price. From 1973&ndash;79 the thresholds were based on monetary revenue: Platinum (Pound sterling|£1,000,000), Gold (£150,000 from April 1973 to September 1974, £250,000 from September 1974 to January 1977, and £300,000 from 1977 until 1979) and Silver (£75,000 from April 1973 to January 1975, £100,000 from January 1975 to January 1977, and £150,000 from 1977 until 1979).<ref>cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/assets/files/Certified%20Awards%20Timeline.pdf|title=Certified Awards &ndash; A Timeline|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|accessdate=2010-12-01|format=PDF</ref><br />
note|Europe| XIII Awarded for actual retail sales in the following countries: Austria, Belgium, Bulgaria, Czech Republic, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Hungary, Iceland, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Portugal, Russia, Serbia, Slovakia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, Turkey and United Kingdom.<br />
note|South Korea| XIV South Korean physical album sales exceeding 1,000,000 are given the "Million" award.<br />
note|Romania| XV Although UPFR's certifications levels have never been clearly defined, it is known that they have been repeatedly lowered since their introduction, due to heavy music piracy and financial crisises in Romania.<ref name="taifas">cite news|url=http://taifasuri.ro/taifasuri/mozaic/5848-71-de-ani-de-la-primul-disc-de-aur-nr358-sapt09-feb-15-feb-2012|title=71 de ani de la primul Disc de Aur|trans-title=71 years from the first gold award|author=Șerban, Elena|publisher='':ro:Taifasuri|Taifasuri''|language=Romanian|accessdate=27 June 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628015448/http://taifasuri.ro/taifasuri/mozaic/5848-71-de-ani-de-la-primul-disc-de-aur-nr358-sapt09-feb-15-feb-2012|archivedate=28 June 2018|df=</ref><ref>cite news|url=https://www.agentiadepresamondena.com/cum-a-cazut-industria-muzicala-romaneasca-inna-abia-a-primit-discul-de-aur/|date=9 November 2011|title=Cum a cazut industria muzicala romaneasca: Inna abia a primit discul de aur|trans-title=How the music industry declined in Romania: Inna has just been awarded gold|author=Dutoiu, Sorin|publisher=Agenția de Presă Mondenă|language=Romanian|accessdate=27 June 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130213011843/http://www.agentiadepresamondena.com/cum-a-cazut-industria-muzicala-romaneasca-inna-abia-a-primit-discul-de-aur/|archivedate=13 February 2013|df=</ref><ref name="l1">cite news|url=http://evz.ro/muzica-in-coma-vanzari-de-10-ori-mai-mici-897344.html|title=Muzica, în comă: vânzări de 10 ori mai mici|trans-title=The music, in coma: sales 10 times lower|publisher=''Evenimentul Zilei''|date=5 June 2010|accessdate=28 May 2018|language=Romanian|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528200358/http://evz.ro/muzica-in-coma-vanzari-de-10-ori-mai-mici-897344.html|archivedate=28 May 2018|df=</ref><ref name="criza">cite web | url=http://jurnalul.ro/stire-antimonden/criza-loveste-si-in-discurile-de-aur-515024.html | title=Criza loveşte şi în Discurile de aur| trans-title=The crisis also hits the Gold certifications|language=Romanian | publisher=''Jurnalul''| accessdate=28 May 2018|date=19 July 2009|author=Cobuz, Dana</ref> UPFR's certifications are based on both the units sold and the sales price of an album.<ref name="stratan"/> List of certified albums in Romania|Several awards have been handed out since the early 1990s.

